SIMPLE: whirl
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whirl
<hw>Whirl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Whirled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whirling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>whirlen</ets>,
probably from the Scand.; cf. Icel. & Sw. <ets>hvirfla</ets>, Dan.
<ets>hvirvle</ets>; akin to D. <ets>wervelen</ets>, G.
<ets>wirbeln</ets>, freq. of the verb seen in Icel. <ets>hverfa</ets> to
turn. ⟦root⟧16. See <er>Wharf</er>, and cf. <er>Warble</er>,
<er>Whorl</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn round rapidly; to cause to rotate with
velocity; to make to revolve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>whirls</qex> his sword around without delay.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remove or carry quickly with, or as with, a
revolving motion; to snatch; to harry.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See, see the chariot, and those rushing wheels,⟦br⟧
That <qex>whirled</qex> the prophet up at Chebar flood.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The passionate heart of the poet is <qex>whirl'd</qex> into
folly.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whirl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whirl
<hw>Whirl</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To be turned round rapidly; to move round with
velocity; to revolve or rotate with great speed; to gyrate.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>whirling</xex> year vainly my dizzy eyes pursue.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>J. H. Newman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wooden engine flies and <qex>whirls</qex> about.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move hastily or swiftly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But <qex>whirled</qex> away to shun his hateful sight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whirl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whirl
<hw>Whirl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Dan. <ets>hvirvel</ets>, Sw.
<ets>hvirfvel</ets>, Icel. <ets>hvirfill</ets> the crown of the head, G.
<ets>wirbel</ets> whirl, crown of the head, D. <ets>wervel</ets>. See
<er>Whirl</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A turning with rapidity or velocity; rapid rotation
or circumvolution; quick gyration; rapid or confusing motion; <as>as,
the <ex>whirl</ex> of a top; the <ex>whirl</ex> of a wheel</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In no breathless <xex>whirl</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>J. H.
Newman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rapid . . . <qex>whirl</qex> of things here below interrupt
not the inviolable rest and calmness of the noble beings above.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything that moves with a whirling
motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He saw Falmouth under gray, iron skies, and <qex>whirls</qex> of
March dust.</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A revolving hook used in twisting, as the hooked
spindle of a rope machine, to which the threads to be twisted are
attached.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot. & Zool.)</fld> <def>A whorl. See
<er>Whorl</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whirlabout</ent>⟦br⟧
